<HR>
<HR>
<HR>
<HR>
<P>
<LI> <FONT COLOR="darkmagenta"><B>
     Converting between different representation systems
     </B></FONT>
<P>
<UL>
<LI> <FONT color="blue"><B>Fact:</B></FONT>
<P>
<UL>
<TABLE bgcolor="lightyellow" BORDER="5">
<TR> <TD>

 <UL>
 <LI> We <B>just</B> learned that
      <FONT color="red"><B>key board/terminal</B></FONT> uses
      the <FONT color="blue"><B>ASCII code</B></FONT> to
      represent
      the <FONT color="red"><B>input/output data</B></FONT>
 </UL>

</TD> </TR>
</TABLE>
</UL>
<P>
<B>Specifically:</B>
<P>
<UL>
<TABLE bgcolor="#CCFFCC" BORDER="5">
<TR> <TD>

<FONT color="blue">
<B>
<PRE>
  The number <FONT color="red">12</FONT> is represented by the <FONT color="red">ASCII codes: 00110001 00110010 (binary)  </FONT> 
</PRE>
</B>
</FONT>

</TD> </TR>
</TABLE>
</UL>
<P>

<HR>
<HR>
<P>
<LI> <FONT color="red"><B>Previously (a few lectures ago)</B></FONT>,
    we studied
      the <FONT color="blue"><B>2'c somplete (numerical value)
     encoding</B></FONT>
   used to <FONT color="red"><B>represent </B></FONT>
   <FONT color="blue"><B><I>signed</I> integer values</B></FONT>:
<P>
<UL>
<TABLE bgcolor="lightyellow" BORDER="5">
<TR> <TD>

<FONT color="blue">
<B>
<PRE>
  In <FONT color="red">2'c complement code</FONT>, the value <FONT color="red">12</FONT> is represented as:       

                                   <FONT color="red">00001100</FONT> (in  8 bits)
			   <FONT color="red">0000000000001100</FONT> (in 16 bits)
	   <FONT color="red">00000000000000000000000000001100</FONT> (in 32 bits)
</PRE>
</B>
</FONT>

</TD> </TR>
</TABLE>
</UL>
<P>
<HR>
<HR>
<P>
<LI> <FONT color="red"><B>Therefore</B></FONT>:
<P>
<UL>
<TABLE bgcolor="lightcyan" BORDER="5">
<TR> <TD>

 <UL>
 <LI> The <FONT color="blue"><B>computer</B></FONT> uses
      <FONT color="red"><B><I>many different</I> representations
      (= encoding methods)</B></FONT>
      for the <FONT color="blue"><B><I>same</I> "information"</B></FONT>
<P>
<UL>
<TABLE bgcolor="#FFEEEE" BORDER="5">
<TR> <TD>

 <UL>
 <LI> The <FONT color="red"><B>encoding method (= representation method)
      the tha <FONT color="blue"><B>computer</B></FONT>
       will use to <FONT color="red"><B>represent the data</B></FONT>
       will </B></FONT> used <FONT color="blue"><B>depend</B></FONT> on
      the <FONT color="red"><B><I>purpose</I> (= context)</B></FONT>
 </UL>

</TD> </TR>
</TABLE>
</UL>
<P>
<B>Example:</B>
<P>
<UL>
<TABLE bgcolor="#CCFFCC" BORDER="5">
<TR> <TD>

 <UL>
 <LI> The <FONT color="blue"><B>computer</B></FONT> uses
     <FONT color="red"><B>2's complement representation</B></FONT> if it 
   <FONT color="blue"><B>needs</B></FONT>
     to <FONT color="red"><B>perform <I>computation</I></B></FONT> on
     the <FONT color="blue"><B>data</B></FONT>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
   <LI> The <FONT color="blue"><B>computer</B></FONT> uses
     <FONT color="red"><B>ASCII representation</B></FONT> if it 
   <FONT color="blue"><B>needs</B></FONT>
     to <FONT color="red"><B> <I>input/output</I></B></FONT> 
     the <FONT color="blue"><B>data</B></FONT> from/to
     a <FONT color="red"><B>key board/terminal</B></FONT>
     
 </UL>

</TD> </TR>
</TABLE>
</UL>
<P>

 </UL>

</TD> </TR>
</TABLE>
</UL>
<P>
<HR>
<HR>
<P>
<LI> Due to the <FONT color="red"><B>existance</B></FONT>
  of  <FONT color="blue"><B>different representation (= encoding)</B></FONT>
    for
 the <FONT color="red"><B><I>same value</I></B></FONT>
   (but for different purposes),
 there is a <B>need</B> to
 <FONT color="blue"><B>convert</B></FONT>
  from one representation to another representation when
  the <FONT color="red"><B>purpose changes</B></FONT>.
<P>
<B>Example:</B> 
    <FONT color="red"><B>integer input</B></FONT>
<P>
<UL>
<TABLE bgcolor="lightyellow" BORDER="5">
<TR> <TD>

 <UL>
 <LI> <FONT color="blue"><B>Suppose</B></FONT>
        the <B>program</B> needs an
     <FONT color="red"><B>integer value</B></FONT> 
     for <FONT color="blue"><B>input</B></FONT> in some
    <FONT color="red"><B>computation</B></FONT>
     
<P>
<UL>
<TABLE bgcolor="#FFEEEE" BORDER="5">
<TR> <TD>

 <UL>
 <LI> Since the <FONT color="blue"><B>integer value</B></FONT>
     is  used for
    <FONT color="red"><B>computation</B></FONT>, we want to use
    the <FONT color="blue"><B>2's complement representation</B></FONT>
    for the <FONT color="red"><B>integer value</B></FONT>
 <P>
 <LI> <FONT color="red"><B>However</B></FONT>, the
    <FONT color="blue"><B>key board device</B></FONT> uses the
    <FONT color="red"><B>ASCII representation</B></FONT> for
    the <FONT color="blue"><B>input data</B></FONT>
 <P>
   <FONT color="blue"><B>That means:</B></FONT>
    when the user types in:
<P>
<UL>
<TABLE bgcolor="lightyellow" BORDER="5">
<TR> <TD>

<FONT color="blue">
<B>
<PRE>
    12      
</PRE>
</B>
</FONT>

</TD> </TR>
</TABLE>
</UL>
<P>
The <FONT color="red"><B>computer</B></FONT> will
  receive these
  <FONT color="blue"><B>ASCII codes</B></FONT> as
 <FONT color="red"><B>input</B></FONT>:
<P>
<UL>
<TABLE bgcolor="lightyellow" BORDER="5">
<TR> <TD>

<FONT color="blue">
<B>
<PRE>
    00110001 00110010          
</PRE>
</B>
</FONT>

</TD> </TR>
</TABLE>
</UL>
<P>
But in order to perform
 <FONT color="red"><B>computation</B></FONT>, the
 <FONT color="blue"><B>number 12</B></FONT> must be
 represented by
 <FONT color="red"><B><TT>00000000000000000000000000001100</TT></B></FONT> !!





<P>
<HR>
<P>
<LI> <FONT color="red"><B>Therefore</B></FONT>:
<P>
<UL>
<TABLE bgcolor="#CCFFCC" BORDER="5">
<TR> <TD>

 <UL>
 <LI> We need to <FONT color="red"><B>convert</B></FONT> the
    <FONT color="blue"><B>ASCII input representation</B></FONT>
    (emitted by the keyboard) to
    the corresponing
    <FONT color="red"><B>2's complement representation</B></FONT>
 </UL>

</TD> </TR>
</TABLE>
</UL>
<P>
BTW: that's is why you need to use the following construct to read in
  <FONT color="red"><B>numbers</B></FONT> in 
  a <FONT color="blue"><B>Java program</B></FONT>:
<P>
<UL>
<TABLE bgcolor="lightcyan" BORDER="5">
<TR> <TD>

<FONT color="blue">
<B>
<PRE>
    String s = in.next( );       // Read input - it's always in ASCII code

    int    i = <FONT color="red">Integer.parseInt( s )</FONT>; // Convert ASCII repr to 2's compl repr
</PRE>
</B>
</FONT>

</TD> </TR>
</TABLE>
</UL>
<P>
(The method <FONT color="red"><B><TT>in.nextInt( )</TT></B></FONT>
 combines the
  <FONT color="blue"><B><TT>in.next( )</TT></B></FONT> and
 the <FONT color="red"><B><TT>Integer.parseInt( )</TT></B></FONT> for
 your convenience.)


 </UL>

</TD> </TR>
</TABLE>
</UL>
<P>

 </UL>

</TD> </TR>
</TABLE>
</UL>
<P>
<HR>
<HR>
<P>
<LI> We will next study 2 conversion methods:
<P>
<UL>
<TABLE bgcolor="lightcyan" BORDER="5">
<TR> <TD>

 <OL>
 <LI> <FONT color="red"><B>ASCII representation</B></FONT> 
         <-->
	 <FONT color="blue"><B>Boolean representation</B></FONT>
   (This is a very simple conversion and I use it to
   introduce the next harder one)
 <P>
 <LI> <FONT color="red"><B>ASCII representation</B></FONT> 
         <-->
	 <FONT color="blue"><B><TT>int</TT> 2's complement 
     representation</B></FONT>
 </OL>

</TD> </TR>
</TABLE>
</UL>
<P>

  </UL>
</UL>
